CHAPTER I

INTRODUCTION


1.1 INTRODUCTION

India’s vast and varied climatic zones necessitate region-specific strategies for energy-efficient building design. Among these, the tropical climate of Raipur, characterized by high temperatures and humidity, poses significant challenges to maintaining thermal comfort indoors without relying heavily on mechanical cooling systems. In such hot and humid environments, the design of building envelopes—particularly wall assemblies—plays a crucial role in regulating indoor temperatures and reducing energy consumption.

Conventional wall constructions often fail to mitigate heat gain effectively, leading to increased indoor temperatures and higher cooling demands. This results not only in greater operational energy usage but also escalates electricity costs and environmental impact. As a solution, the use of advanced insulating materials within wall structures can significantly improve thermal resistance, acting as a barrier against external heat infiltration and thus lowering the cooling load.

This project focuses on Raipur as a case study to analyze the effect of different insulating materials on indoor room temperature using MATLAB simulations. The selected materials include Expanded Polystyrene (EPS) paired with wood, EPS combined with aluminum foil, and Medium Density Fiberboard Panels (MDFP). Each material combination will be evaluated for its thermal performance, associated cooling load, and cost-effectiveness.

Through this comparative analysis, the study aims to identify sustainable wall configurations that offer optimal thermal insulation tailored to Raipur’s climate. By integrating thermal simulation with cost analysis, the outcomes will support data-driven decisions for energy-efficient, climate-responsive building design in tropical regions like Raipur.

1.1.1 Introduction to MATLAB in Building Thermal Analysis

MATLAB (Matrix Laboratory) is a powerful computational platform extensively used in engineering, scientific research, and academic environments for its high-level programming capabilities and robust mathematical toolsets. In the context of building performance analysis, MATLAB serves as an essential tool for simulating heat transfer, energy consumption, and thermal comfort under various material properties and environmental conditions.

For hot and humid regions like Raipur, where high ambient temperatures and solar radiation significantly contribute to indoor heat gain, MATLAB proves especially valuable. It allows researchers and building designers to evaluate and compare different wall insulation strategies aimed at reducing thermal load and improving energy efficiency.

By utilizing built-in toolboxes such as Simulink, Control System Toolbox, and thermal modeling functions, users can create dynamic simulations that reflect real-world thermal behavior across different times of the day, seasons, and construction assemblies. MATLAB also supports integration with real-time climate data and meteorological databases, which enhances the accuracy of simulations by tailoring them to the specific climatic conditions of Raipur.

Moreover, MATLAB enables the development of custom algorithms for iterative analysis, optimization of insulation thickness, and cost-performance evaluation. This helps in identifying the most efficient insulation material and configuration, making it an indispensable tool in designing energy-conscious and climate-responsive buildings.



1.2 OBJECTIVE

The primary objective of this report is to analyze and compare the thermal performance of various wall insulation materials with the goal of reducing heat transfer and minimizing the cooling load in buildings. By evaluating multiple insulation options under consistent environmental and structural conditions, this study aims to:

  • Quantitatively assess the impact of different insulation materials on the rate of heat transfer through building walls.

  • Compare the cooling load requirements associated with each material to determine their effectiveness in improving indoor thermal comfort.

  • Identify the most suitable insulation material based on a balance of thermal resistance, material cost, ease of installation, and suitability for different climatic conditions.

  • Provide data-driven recommendations for selecting optimal insulation materials in the context of energy-efficient building design.

Through this analysis, the report seeks to contribute toward sustainable construction practices by supporting informed decisions in material selection that align with energy conservation goals and long-term operational efficiency.

CHAPTER II

CASE STUDY

2.1 CASE STUDY

In regions with high ambient temperatures and intense humidity like Raipur, Chhattisgarh (India), maintaining thermal comfort in buildings requires significant cooling energy. A major contributor to indoor heat gain is conduction through building walls, which makes the selection of suitable insulation materials a critical factor in improving energy efficiency and reducing operational costs.

This case study focuses on analyzing the thermal performance of different wall insulation materials to determine the most effective solution for minimizing heat transfer and cooling load in such a climate. The primary objective is to identify the optimal insulation material that balances both thermal efficiency and economic feasibility.

2.2 Scope of Study

This case study is centered around the thermal analysis of a standardized room model located in Raipur, Chhattisgarh, with the objective of identifying the most effective wall insulation material for reducing heat transfer and cooling load in hot and humid conditions.

2.2.1 Location Overview: Raipur, Chhattisgarh

Raipur, the capital city of Chhattisgarh, lies in the heart of India and is rapidly developing as an industrial and urban hub. Geographically positioned in the tropical zone, Raipur experiences extreme climatic conditions, making it highly relevant for evaluating building insulation strategies.

  • Climate Profile:
     Raipur falls under the Tropical Wet and Dry (Aw) climate classification according to the Köppen system. Summers are particularly harsh, with temperatures often exceeding 45°C, accompanied by high humidity levels ranging from 60% to 80% during the pre-monsoon and monsoon periods. The annual average temperature remains above 27°C, and the mean solar radiation is considerably high, especially from March to June.


Figure 2. Location in India

  • Energy Demand and Urban Growth:
     Due to increasing urbanization, Raipur has seen a significant rise in energy consumption, particularly for space cooling in residential and commercial buildings. Air conditioners and fans are used extensively to manage thermal discomfort, which contributes to peak electricity loads during summer. This makes thermal efficiency and passive cooling strategies crucial for sustainable development in the region.

  • Ideal Case for Study:
     The consistent high heat gain, coupled with growing construction activity, makes Raipur a model city for thermal performance analysis. The challenges it presents are representative of many Tier-II cities across India, where energy-efficient, low-cost, and climatically responsive construction practices are in high demand.

2.2.2 Room Specifications

The study considers a standardized room with dimensions 10 FEET × 10 FEET × 10 FEET, representing a simplified but scalable model for both residential and commercial spaces. This uniform geometry ensures consistency in simulation and comparison of heat transfer across different wall configurations.

2.2.3 Insulation Materials Evaluated

To determine the best-performing wall structure, the following materials are evaluated:

1. Normal Brick Wall (Uninsulated Case)

Description

The normal brick wall represents the conventional construction method commonly used in residential and small commercial buildings across India. This wall type typically consists of burnt clay bricks laid with mortar (usually cement-sand mix), with or without plaster finishes on either side.

  • Establish the baseline energy performance

  • Identify the relative improvement provided by other insulation materials

  • Assess energy savings and cost benefits of applying insulation over the conventional approach


In summary, while the normal brick wall is structurally sound and economically viable, it lacks thermal efficiency, especially in climates like Raipur's, and highlights the need for improved wall assemblies in future constructions.

2. Expanded Polystyrene (EPS) Insulated Wall

Description

Expanded Polystyrene (EPS) is a lightweight, rigid, closed-cell insulation material made from expanded beads of polystyrene resin. It is widely used in thermal insulation for buildings due to its excellent heat resistance, affordability, and ease of installation. In this case, EPS is applied as a layer on the inner face of the brick wall to evaluate its impact on heat transfer reduction.

EPS insulation works by trapping air within its cellular structure, which significantly limits conductive and convective heat flow, making it particularly effective for hot climates like that of Raipur.

2.3Material Properties

The thermal and physical properties of EPS used in this analysis are as follows:

  • Thermal Conductivity: ~0.032 – 0.038 W/m·K

  • Density: ~15 – 30 kg/m³

  • Specific Heat Capacity: ~1300 J/kg·K


Thermal Performance

When added to the brick wall assembly, EPS significantly enhances thermal resistance by forming a barrier that slows down the inward heat transfer. Key thermal benefits observed in the simulation include:

  • Lower heat gain through the wall during peak outdoor temperatures

  • Reduction in cooling load, leading to energy savings

  • Improved indoor comfort, especially in non-air-conditioned spaces

EPS helps in flattening the temperature fluctuations inside the room, which is crucial for thermal stability in a city like Raipur, where daytime heat is intense and prolonged.

Purpose in the Study

EPS is tested in this study as a practical, cost-effective insulation option. Its inclusion aims to:

  • Evaluate how a simple insulation retrofit can improve the thermal efficiency of existing brick walls

  • Quantify the reduction in cooling load compared to the uninsulated case

  • Assess the material’s suitability in terms of performance and installation feasibility in the Indian construction context

Advantages

  • High insulation efficiency per unit thickness

  • Low cost and widely available

  • Lightweight and easy to handle

  • Resistant to moisture absorption and microbial growth


Limitations

  • Flammable unless treated with fire retardants

  • Not UV-resistant—requires protection from direct sunlight

  • Not biodegradable, raising sustainability concerns


3. Medium Density Fiberboard Panel (MDFP) Insulated Wall

Description

Medium Density Fiberboard Panel (MDFP) is a type of engineered wood product made by compressing wood fibers with wax and resin binders under high temperature and pressure. Though traditionally used for furniture and interior woodwork, MDF panels are gaining attention as an alternative wall insulation layer due to their moderate thermal resistance, smooth surface finish, and eco-friendliness when sourced from recycled wood.

In this study, MDFP is applied to the inner surface of the standard brick wall to analyze its impact on indoor temperature regulation and cooling load in a hot and humid environment like Raipur.

2.3Material Properties

Thermal Performance

While MDFP does not provide as high insulation performance as specialized materials like EPS, it still contributes to a moderate reduction in heat transfer due to its relatively low thermal conductivity compared to brick. The simulation indicates that:

  • Indoor heat gain is reduced, though not as significantly as with high-performance insulations

  • Cooling load shows improvement over the uninsulated brick case

  • The material adds thermal mass, which helps buffer short-term temperature fluctuations


Its contribution is particularly notable in evening and night hours, where its thermal inertia helps delay heat release, thereby maintaining comfort for longer periods.

Purpose in the Study

The inclusion of MDFP serves two objectives:

  • To examine a wood-based alternative that offers thermal improvement with aesthetic and structural benefits

  • To determine its cost-to-benefit viability in terms of insulation performance and material affordability in the Indian market


Advantages

  • Moderate insulation performance with thermal inertia

  • Smooth, paintable finish suitable for interiors

  • Environmentally friendly when made from recycled wood

  • Easy to install and handle


Limitations

  • Not highly moisture resistant—requires sealing in humid environments like Raipur

  • Lower insulation performance compared to synthetic insulators like EPS

  • Can swell or warp if exposed to water over time

  • Combustible, unless fire-treated

4. Expanded Polystyrene with Aluminium Foil (EPSF) Insulated Wall



Description

EPSF refers to Expanded Polystyrene (EPS) insulation enhanced with an aluminium foil facing on one or both sides. This composite material combines the excellent insulating properties of EPS with the reflective capabilities of aluminium foil, making it highly effective in minimizing heat gain from both conduction and radiation.

In this configuration, the EPS layer provides thermal resistance, while the aluminium foil acts as a radiant barrier, reflecting a significant portion of incoming thermal radiation. This is particularly beneficial in hot climates like Raipur, where solar heat gain plays a major role in increasing indoor temperatures.

Material Properties

Typical thermal and physical properties of EPSF used in the study:

  • Thermal Conductivity (EPS core): ~0.032 – 0.038 W/m·K

  • Emissivity of Aluminium Foil: ~0.03 – 0.05 (very low, highly reflective)

  • Density: ~15 – 30 kg/m³

  • Specific Heat Capacity: ~1300 J/kg·K




Thermal Performance

EPSF significantly outperforms regular EPS due to its dual-action mechanism:

  • The EPS core reduces conductive heat transfer

  • The aluminium foil reflects radiant heat, preventing it from entering the wall structure


Simulation results for Raipur’s climate show that EPSF:

  • Greatly reduces indoor heat gain, even during peak sunlight hours

  • Lowers cooling load more effectively than standard EPS

  • Enhances thermal comfort by reducing indoor temperature rise, especially in non-AC buildings or during power outages


Purpose in the Study

EPSF is included in the study as a premium insulation variant, offering enhanced performance in radiation-dominated environments. The objective is to:

  • Measure the added benefit of using a radiant barrier over standard EPS

  • Analyze whether the incremental cost translates into a proportionate energy saving

  • Evaluate its suitability in high-exposure walls, such as south- and west-facing facades in Raipur


Advantages

  • Superior insulation performance compared to plain EPS

  • Reflects up to 95% of radiant heat

  • Lightweight and easy to install

  • Moisture resistant and durable

  • Ideal for both new constructions and retrofitting existing walls




Limitations

  • Slightly higher cost than standard EPS

  • Requires careful installation to maintain foil integrity and avoid air gaps

  • Foil can degrade under prolonged UV exposure—needs protection behind cladding or plaster.



5. Mud Brick Wall (Traditional Earth Construction)

Description

Mud bricks, also known as adobe or earthen bricks, are one of the oldest known building materials, traditionally made from a mix of soil (clay and silt), sand, water, and natural fibers such as straw. Once shaped, they are left to sun-dry rather than being kiln-fired, resulting in a low-energy, eco-friendly material. In many rural and semi-urban parts of India, including regions near Raipur, mud brick construction is still in use due to its availability, affordability, and thermal comfort.

In this study, the mud brick wall is modeled as a standalone structural and thermal envelope, not as an insulation layer over a standard brick wall. It is evaluated for its thermal efficiency in comparison to modern insulation strategies.

Material Properties

Typical values considered for sun-dried mud bricks in the simulation:

  • Thermal Conductivity: ~0.25 – 0.35 W/m·K

  • Density: ~1500 – 1700 kg/m³

  • Specific Heat Capacity: ~1000 – 1100 J/kg·K


Thermal Performance

Mud brick walls provide good thermal mass and moderate insulation, making them naturally suited for hot and dry climates. In the context of Raipur, they offer several performance advantages:

  • Delayed heat transfer into the building due to thermal inertia

  • More stable indoor temperatures, especially during peak daytime heat

  • Natural regulation of humidity, enhancing comfort without mechanical cooling

  • Reduced cooling load compared to normal fired brick walls


The walls absorb heat slowly during the day and release it gradually at night, which helps buffer indoor temperatures and supports passive cooling strategies.

Purpose in the Study

To compare vernacular architecture practices with modern insulation systems
he inclusion of mud brick serves multiple objectives:

  • To evaluate the performance of traditional, low-cost, eco-friendly construction

  • To assess the potential of mud construction as a sustainable alternative, particularly in low-income or rural development.

Advantages

  • Good thermal inertia, ideal for hot climates

  • Environmentally friendly and low embodied energy

  • Locally sourced and biodegradable materials

  • Cost-effective with minimal processing

  • Naturally breathable, allowing moisture regulation indoors


Limitations

  • Low structural strength compared to fired brick or concrete

  • Vulnerable to water damage—requires protective plaster or cladding

CHAPTER III

LITERATURE REVIEW



3.1 Literature Review on Thermal Analysis for Raipur Region Using Different Insulating Materials

Thermal performance analysis is vital in evaluating energy efficiency and occupant comfort, particularly in diverse climatic regions like Raipur, which experiences high solar radiation and intense summer temperatures. Several studies across India have focused on optimizing building thermal behavior using different materials and passive design strategies. This review consolidates insights from key sources and contextualizes them for potential application in the Raipur region.

3.1.1 Thermal Flexibility in Buildings

This study assesses thermal comfort and heating practices in European households but provides insights applicable to Indian contexts, especially regarding flexible energy systems. Key findings include:

1. Temperature Variability: The research highlights that indoor temperatures vary spatially and temporally, influenced by activities, material properties, and socio-demographic factors. For example, temperature differences between spaces in the same apartment can reach 7°C .

2. Thermal Mass Activation: The concept of modulating energy demand through thermal mass—using building walls and floors to store heat—is examined. This practice is particularly relevant in regions with intermittent energy sources .

3. Occupant Behavior: Thermal preferences and heating practices are influenced by social and cultural dynamics, underlining the need for region-specific solutions.


3.1.2 Literature Review:

The same study compared mud-based construction with RCC (reinforced cement concrete) and showed that the former led to significant energy savings—up to 3,294 kWh/year—due to reduced heating and cooling demands. While mud offers high thermal mass, it lacks the insulation performance of modern materials like EPS (expanded polystyrene) and MDFE (metallic reflective foils with insulation layers), which are more suitable for rapid, modular constructions needed in urbanizing zones like Raipur.

1.Thermal Performance of Passive Houses
 The concept of passive houses, like the one discussed in Tiwari and Chel's work, emphasizes natural thermal comfort achieved through the use of low thermal conductivity materials. In the case of mud-houses, the walls and roofs made from adobe and stabilized mud blocks provide superior insulation by attenuating temperature fluctuations. These structures often include energy-efficient thermal mass, which helps in both heating and cooling regulation . This approach could be enhanced further with EPSW (Expanded Polystyrene Wall) and EPSF (Expanded Polystyrene Floor) as modern alternatives to traditional mud walls, offering high insulation and lower heat conductivity .


2.Insulation Materials for Passive Buildings
 EPSW and EPSF are increasingly used for their excellent thermal insulation properties. EPS materials are lightweight and provide effective barrier against heat flow, thus significantly improving the energy performance of buildings. When combined with MDFP (Medium Density Fiberboard Panel), these materials can help maintain stable indoor temperatures across varying climates .


3.Energy and CO2 Emission Savings
 Passive houses have demonstrated significant energy savings. For example, the passive house studied in Tiwari and Chel’s research saved approximately 1481 kWh/year in heating and 1813 kWh/year in cooling compared to conventional buildings . The reduction in energy consumption is accompanied by a substantial reduction in CO2 emissions, estimated at 5.2 metric tons per year, providing a clear benefit for rural and semi-urban construction .


4.Embodied Energy Considerations
 The embodied energy of building materials is another critical factor for sustainable construction. The research compares embodied energy in mud-houses versus conventional RCC (Reinforced Cement Concrete) structures. While mud-based passive houses generally have lower embodied energy and associated CO2 emissions, modern materials like EPSW can further reduce embodied energy when compared to traditional brick or cement-based constructions .

3.2 Modern Insulation Materials:

3.2.1. Expanded Polystyrene (EPS) Insulation
EPS (ρ ≈ 15–30 kg/m³) offers thermal conductivity λ ≈ 0.030–0.040 W/m·K and high R‑values per unit thickness. Commercially used as exterior insulation finish systems (EIFS) and under‑slab floor insulation, EPS has embodied energy ~100–120 MJ/m³ and is inert, moisture‑resistant, and long‑lasting.

3.2.2 Expanded Polystyrene Floor (EPSF) Panels
Under‑slab EPSF panels (e.g., 25–100 mm thick) decouple indoor spaces from ground‑coupled heat loss.

3.2.3 Medium‑Density Fiber Panels (MDFP)
MDF panels (ρ ≈ 600–800 kg/m³) are engineered wood composites with λ ≈ 0.12–0.15 W/m·K. Used as internal finishing, MDFP provides moderate insulation and thermal storage, while offering a stable substrate for vapor barriers

Environmental and Economic Impacts
Embodied energy for EPSW/EPSF is comparable to or lower than brick/mud, while offering higher R‑values per unit thickness. Combined with the low‑carbon profile of MDFP, overall embodied carbon can be held below 500 kgCO₂e/m²—well under conventional EIFS or masonry walls (800–1,200 kgCO₂e/m²)

3.3 Discussion

The present study extends the conversation around thermal efficiency by focusing on a controlled room setup insulated with three modern materials: EPSF (Expanded Polystyrene Foil-faced), EPSW (Expanded Polystyrene White), and MDFP (Medium Density Foil Panel). Unlike traditional approaches that primarily explore high thermal mass materials such as mudbrick or adobe, our objective is to evaluate how lightweight, modern insulators perform in reducing indoor temperatures, cooling loads, and operational costs in a hot and composite climate like Raipur.

Our analysis highlights that material selection and placement strategy are pivotal in passive design. While mud and straw provide inherent thermal mass benefits, materials like EPSF and MDFP bring distinct advantages in radiant heat reflection and installation convenience, particularly in urban or modular buildings. Among them, EPSF shows the most balanced performance—offering both conductive and radiant insulation, which proves beneficial for top-floor dwellings exposed to direct sunlight. EPSW, though slightly less effective against radiant heat, still performs well in wall cavity applications, especially in combination with ventilated designs.

MDFP, with its high reflectivity and quick thermal response, demonstrates excellent performance under metal roofs, a common feature in cost-sensitive urban housing. Its reflective layers, when used with an air gap, create a thermal envelope that effectively delays heat ingress into the living space, thereby reducing reliance on mechanical cooling systems.

Another critical takeaway is the alignment of indoor thermal performance with energy cost reductions. The use of these insulating materials has shown the potential to lower cooling energy demand, thereby minimizing electricity bills—an essential consideration for economically sensitive regions. This outcome reinforces the need for targeted material solutions that address both thermal comfort and affordability.

Furthermore, while this study emphasizes technical efficiency, it also acknowledges that occupant behavior, cultural practices, and thermal comfort preferences significantly influence real-world performance. The interaction between user habits—such as ventilation patterns, usage timings, and shading practices—and building material properties must be explored further in future localized research.

In summary, this study demonstrates that strategic insulation using EPSF, EPSW, and MDFP can deliver measurable improvements in indoor comfort and energy efficiency. It also signals a shift from purely traditional thermal mass strategies to hybrid models that leverage both modern materials and passive design thinking, tailored for rapidly urbanizing and climate-sensitive zones like Raipur.

3.4 Passive Houses in India

The case study by Chel & Tiwari (2009) on a passive mud-house in Delhi illustrates the potential for eco-friendly architecture in Indian regions. Insights include:

1. Climate Suitability: The mud-house, with its vaulted roof and thick mud walls, minimizes temperature fluctuations, making it ideal for composite climates. This can be replicated in other regions with similar climatic conditions .

2. Energy Efficiency: By reducing reliance on active cooling and heating systems, the house achieves significant energy savings. The cooling energy savings (1,813 kWh annually) highlight the potential for passive designs in hot regions .

3. Carbon Mitigation: The annual CO2 mitigation of 5.2 metric tons per house underscores the environmental benefits of adopting traditional materials and passive designs. This aligns with India's climate action goals under the Paris Agreement .

3.5 Comparative Insights Across Regions : Analyzing the thermal performance of building materials and designs in different Indian regions reveals:

1. Hot and Dry Zones: Regions like Rajasthan benefit from high thermal mass materials (e.g., mudbrick), which stabilize indoor temperatures despite extreme outdoor conditions.

2. Humid Regions: In areas like Kerala, passive cooling techniques such as cross-ventilation and reflective surfaces complement materials like straw bales.

3. Cold Regions: Himalayan states require materials that retain heat during cold winters, and innovations such as thermal mass activation could be explored .





CHAPTER - IV

METHODOLOGY



This chapter outlines the detailed methodology employed to evaluate the effectiveness of different insulation materials in reducing heat transfer and cooling load in buildings. The objective is to understand and quantify how insulation materials influence the thermal performance of a building by applying fundamental heat transfer principles. The analysis involves the use of thermodynamic equations, simulation tools, and parameter estimation techniques.

Fig 3. Detail showing conventional burnt clay brick wall with thermal insulation

4.1. Energy Balance Equation for a Room (Heat Transfer Approach)

The first and foremost step in thermal performance analysis is applying the First Law of Thermodynamics for a control volume (the room):


Where:

  • Ma = Mass of air inside the room (kg)

  • Ca = Specific heat of air (~1005 J/kg·K)

  • Tr = Indoor room air temperature (°C)

  • dTr/dt = Rate of temperature change over time

  • Qgain = Total heat gained by the room (W)

  • Qloss = Total heat lost from the room (W)


This fundamental equation helps model the thermal dynamics inside the room. It incorporates all heat gains from the environment and internal sources, as well as losses due to ventilation or structural inefficiencies.

4.2. Heat Gain through Wall: Conduction + Radiation (Sol-Air Concept)

Walls are one of the major components through which heat enters a building. The total heat gain through a wall includes both conductive and radiative components:

  • Uwall​ = Overall heat transfer coefficient of the wall (W/m²·K)

  • Awall = Surface area of the wall (m²)

  • Tsol-air = Sol-air temperature (effective external temperature)

  • Tr = Room air temperature

The sol-air temperature accounts for absorbed solar radiation, making this model more accurate for external wall heat gain, especially in sunny climates.

4.3. Sol-Air Temperature Formula

To account for the effects of solar radiation and ambient conditions, the sol-air temperature is calculated using the following formula:

Where:

  • T_ambient = Outside air temperature (°C)

  • α\alpha = Absorptivity of the wall surface

  • I = Solar radiation intensity on surface (W/m²)

  • εΔR = Net longwave radiation exchange (e.g., 60 W/m² for horizontal surfaces)

  • h_o = External convective heat transfer coefficient (W/m²·K)


Use: This formula translates solar radiation and thermal radiation into an equivalent temperature to plug into the heat transfer formula.



4.4 Overall Heat Transfer Coefficient (U-value)

The U-value represents how well a wall transmits heat. It is derived from the thermal resistances of individual wall layers:

Where:

  • h_i, h_o = Interior and exterior surface heat transfer coefficients (W/m²·K)

  • L_n = Thickness of layer n (m)

  • k_n = Thermal conductivity of layer n (W/m·K)


Lower U-values imply better insulation and less heat transfer. Different insulation materials significantly impact this value, influencing the room’s thermal performance.

5. Heat Gain through Roof

The roof is exposed to direct sunlight throughout the day and can be a dominant factor in total heat gain, especially in tropical or subtropical regions. The same conduction and radiation model as walls is applied to the roof, using relevant surface properties and dimensions.


6. Heat Gain through Windows

Windows allow direct solar radiation into the room, contributing to the internal heat gain:

Where:

  • Awin = Window area (m²)

  • Τ (tau) = Transmissivity of glass (typically ~0.9)

  • Uwin = U-value of glass (~1.84 W/m²·K)


Direct and indirect solar radiation passes through the glass and contributes significantly to the room's heat gain.

7. Internal Heat Generation

  • Q_people ≈ 60 W/person

Depending on occupancy levels and equipment usage, this component can vary significantly and must be estimated carefully for accurate simulations.

8. Heat Loss via Ventilation and Infiltration

Heat is lost from the room due to air exchange with the outside environment. This is modeled using:

  • N = Air changes per hour (ACH)

  • V = Volume of the room (m³)

  • The factor 0.33 comes from , using standard air properties


This term accounts for fresh air entering the room, either intentionally (ventilation) or unintentionally (leakages).



9. Cooling Load Calculation

The total cooling load is computed by summing all sources of heat gain and subtracting the losses. This value helps size air conditioning systems and evaluate the impact of different insulation materials on energy efficiency.

% Constants

rho = 1.225; % air density in kg/m^3

V = 28.32; % room volume in m^3

Ca = 1005; % specific heat capacity of air in J/kg·K

% Initial room temperature (in °C)

T_initial = 25;

% Time settings

dt = 3600; % timestep in seconds (1 hour)

total_hours = 24; % simulate for 24 hours

time = 0:dt:(total_hours*3600);

n = length(time);

% Heat gains/losses in Watts (assumed constant)

Q_wall = 2064.67;

Q_window = 1051.2;

Q_roof = 881.6;

Q_door = 62.06;

Q_internal = 250;

Q_ventilation = 280.11; % heat loss

% Net heat input (in Watts)

Q_total = Q_wall + Q_window + Q_roof + Q_door + Q_internal - Q_ventilation;

% Pre-allocate temperature array

T_room = zeros(1, n);

T_room(1) = T_initial;

% Simulation using Euler's Method

for i = 2:n

dT/dt = Q_total / (rho * V * Ca);

T_room(i) = T_room(i-1) + dTdt * dt;

end

CHAPTER VI

CONCLUSION



6.1 Descriptive Result and Conclusion:

The bar graph illustrates the comparative thermal performance of four different wall insulation strategies, evaluated based on wall heat gain, total heat gain, and rate of temperature rise inside a standard room of volume 28.32 m³.

Observations:

  • Without insulation, the room experiences the highest wall heat gain (2064.67 W) and a total heat gain of 4086.42 W, leading to the fastest temperature rise at 0.1172 K/s.

  • EPS with air gaps significantly reduces the wall heat gain to 541.59 W, decreasing the rate of indoor temperature rise to 0.0719 K/s.

  • MDFP with air gaps, though slightly less effective than EPS, still offers notable improvement with a wall heat gain of 619.31 W and a moderate temperature rise of 0.0741 K/s.

  • EPS + Aluminium Foil with air gaps emerges as the most effective solution, reducing wall heat gain drastically to 260.79 W and achieving the lowest temperature rise rate of 0.0638 K/s.

Final Conclusion:

Based on the detailed thermal evaluation and graphical comparison:

  • The EPS + Aluminium Foil composite insulation with 4 air gaps and a total thickness of 11 cm demonstrates superior thermal performance.

  • It effectively minimizes conductive heat transfer and delays internal air temperature rise, making it the optimal choice for thermal comfort and energy efficiency in room insulation.

Recommendation:
For sustainable building design and enhanced indoor climate control, it is highly recommended to utilize EPS + Aluminium Foil composite insulation in wall assemblies, especially in thermally active zones or hot climates.



Plot 1: Wall vs Total Heat Gain

  • This line plot demonstrates the decrease in wall heat gain with each insulation improvement.

  • While total heat gain also decreases, the impact of wall insulation is significant, especially when using EPS + Foil.
